.TH "runsv" "8" 
.SH NAME
runsv \- starts and monitors a service and optionally an appendant log
service
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]runsv\f[R] \f[I]service\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[I]service\f[R] must be a directory.
.PP
\f[B]runsv\f[R] switches to the directory \f[I]service\f[R] and starts
\&./run.
If ./run exits and ./finish exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R] starts ./finish.
If ./finish doesn\[aq]t exist or ./finish exits, \f[B]runsv\f[R]
restarts ./run.
.PP
If ./run or ./finish exit immediately, \f[B]runsv\f[R] waits a second
before starting ./finish or restarting ./run.
.PP
Two arguments are given to ./finish.
The first one is ./run\[aq]s exit code, or \-1 if ./run didn\[aq]t exit
normally.
The second one is the least significant byte of the exit status as
determined by \f[B]waitpid\f[R](2); for instance it is 0 if ./run exited
normally, and the signal number if ./run was terminated by a signal.
If \f[B]runsv\f[R] cannot start ./run for some reason, the exit code is
111 and the status is 0.
.PP
If the file \f[I]service\f[R]/down exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R] does not
start ./run immediately.
The control interface (see below) can be used to start the service and
to give other commands to \f[B]runsv\f[R].
.PP
If the directory \f[I]service\f[R]/log exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R] creates a
pipe, redirects \f[I]service\f[R]/run\[aq]s and
\f[I]service\f[R]/finish\[aq]s standard output to the pipe, switches to
the directory \f[I]service\f[R]/log and starts ./run.
The standard input of \f[I]service\f[R]/log/run is redirected to read
from the pipe.
.PP
\f[B]runsv\f[R] maintains status information in a binary format
(compatible to the daemontools\[aq] \f[B]supervise\f[R] program) in
\f[I]service\f[R]/supervise/status and
\f[I]service\f[R]/log/supervise/status, and in a human\-readable format
in \f[I]service\f[R]/supervise/stat,
\f[I]service\f[R]/log/supervise/stat, \f[I]service\f[R]/supervise/pid,
\f[I]service\f[R]/log/supervise/pid.
.SH CONTROL
The named pipes \f[I]service\f[R]/supervise/control, and (optionally)
\f[I]service\f[R]/log/supervise/control are provided to give commands to
\f[B]runsv\f[R].
You can use \f[B]sv\f[R](8) to control the service or just write one of
the following characters to the named pipe:
.TP
\f[B]u\f[R]
Up.
If the service is not running, start it.
If the service stops, restart it.
.TP
\f[B]d\f[R]
Down.
If the service is running, send it a TERM signal, and then a CONT
signal.
If ./run exits, start ./finish if it exists.
After it stops, do not restart service.
.TP
\f[B]o\f[R]
Once.
If the service is not running, start it.
Do not restart it if it stops.
.TP
\f[B]p\f[R]
Pause.
If the service is running, send it a STOP signal.
.TP
\f[B]c\f[R]
Continue.
If the service is running, send it a CONT signal.
.TP
\f[B]h\f[R]
Hangup.
If the service is running, send it a HUP signal.
.TP
\f[B]a\f[R]
Alarm.
If the service is running, send it a ALRM signal.
.TP
\f[B]i\f[R]
Interrupt.
If the service is running, send it a INT signal.
.TP
\f[B]q\f[R]
Quit.
If the service is running, send it a QUIT signal.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
User\-defined 1.
If the service is running, send it a USR1 signal.
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
User\-defined 2.
If the service is running, send it a USR2 signal.
.TP
\f[B]t\f[R]
Terminate.
If the service is running, send it a TERM signal.
.TP
\f[B]k\f[R]
Kill.
If the service is running, send it a KILL signal.
.TP
\f[B]x\f[R]
Exit.
If the service is running, send it a TERM signal, and then a CONT
signal.
Do not restart the service.
If the service is down, and no log service exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R]
exits.
If the service is down and a log service exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R] closes
the standard input of the log service, and waits for it to terminate.
If the log service is down, \f[B]runsv\f[R] exits.
This command is ignored if it is given to
\f[I]service\f[R]/log/supervise/control.
.SS EXAMPLE
To send a TERM signal to the socklog\-unix service, either do
\[lq]\f[CR]sv term /service/socklog\-unix\f[R]\[rq] or
\[lq]\f[CR]printf t >/service/socklog\-unix/supervise/control\f[R]\[rq].
.PP
\f[B]printf\f[R](1) usually blocks if no \f[B]runsv\f[R] process is
running in the service directory.
.SH CUSTOMIZE CONTROL
For each control character \f[I]c\f[R] other than \f[B]o\f[R],
\f[B]d\f[R], and \f[B]x\f[R] sent to the control pipe, \f[B]runsv\f[R]
first checks if \f[I]service\f[R]/control/\f[I]c\f[R] exists and is
executable.
If so, it starts \f[I]service\f[R]/control/\f[I]c\f[R] and waits for it
to terminate, before interpreting the command.
If the program exits with return code 0, \f[B]runsv\f[R] refrains from
sending the service the corresponding signal.
The command \f[B]o\f[R] is always considered as command \f[B]u\f[R].
On command \f[B]d\f[R] first \f[I]service\f[R]/control/t is checked, and
then \f[I]service\f[R]/control/d.\ On command \f[B]x\f[R] first
\f[I]service\f[R]/control/t is checked, and then
\f[I]service\f[R]/control/x.
Specifically:
.PP
If the service is running or paused, control characters \f[B]d\f[R] and
\f[B]x\f[R] are handled as follows:
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]runsv\f[R] checks whether \f[I]service\f[R]/control/t exists and is
executable and runs it if yes.
.IP "2." 3
If \f[I]service\f[R]/control/t exits nonzero, or is not executable or
doesn\[aq]t exist, \f[B]runsv\f[R] sends the service a TERM signal.
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]runsv\f[R] sends the service a CONT signal, disregarding
\f[I]service\f[R]/control/c even if it exists and is executable.
.IP "4." 3
\f[B]runsv\f[R] checks whether \f[I]service\f[R]/control/d (or
control/x) exists and is executable and runs it if yes.
Its exit status is ignored.
.PP
The control program runs with the process id of \f[I]service\f[R] as its
first argument, or the empty string if there\[aq]s no pid.
.PP
The control of the optional log service cannot be customized.
.SH SIGNALS
If \f[B]runsv\f[R] receives a TERM signal, it acts as if the character x
was written to the control pipe.
.SH EXIT CODES
\f[B]runsv\f[R] exits 111 on an error on startup or if another
\f[B]runsv\f[R] is running in \f[I]service\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]runsv\f[R] exits 0 if it was told to exit.
